Endpoint Detection with Sysmon + Wazuh
Objectives
By the end of this lab, students will be able to:

Install and configure Sazuh SIEM for centralized log management
Simulate Sysmon event logging on Linux environments
Create custom Wazuh rules and decoders for endpoint detection
Develop Python scripts for automated log parsing and analysis
Implement threat detection workflows using SIEM correlation rules
Prerequisites
Basic Linux command line proficiency
Understanding of SIEM concepts and log analysis
Familiarity with XML and JSON data formats
Basic Python programming knowledge
Understanding of Windows event logging concepts
Lab Environment
Al Nafi Cloud Machine: Click Start Lab to access your pre-configured Ubuntu 20.04 LTS environment with 4GB RAM and 20GB disk space. All commands run on this single cloud instance.

Task 1: Install and Configure Wazuh SIEM
Step 1.1: Install Wazuh Manager
# Create lab directory structure
mkdir -p ~/endpoint-lab/{logs,scripts,configs}
cd ~/endpoint-lab

# Add Wazuh repository
curl -s https://packages.wazuh.com/key/GPG-KEY-WAZUH | gpg --no-default-keyring --keyring gnupg-ring:/usr/share/keyrings/wazuh.gpg --import
sudo chmod 644 /usr/share/keyrings/wazuh.gpg

echo "deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/wazuh.gpg] https://packages.wazuh.com/4.x/apt/ stable main" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/wazuh.list

# Install Wazuh Manager
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y wazuh-manager

# Start Wazuh Manager
sudo systemctl enable wazuh-manager
sudo systemctl start wazuh-manager
sudo systemctl status wazuh-manager
Step 1.2: Install Wazuh Indexer
# Install Wazuh Indexer (OpenSearch)
sudo apt install -y wazuh-indexer

# Configure basic settings
sudo tee /etc/wazuh-indexer/opensearch.yml > /dev/null <<EOF
network.host: 127.0.0.1
node.name: node-1
cluster.initial_master_nodes: ["node-1"]
cluster.name: wazuh-cluster
path.data: /var/lib/wazuh-indexer
path.logs: /var/log/wazuh-indexer
EOF

# Start Wazuh Indexer
sudo systemctl enable wazuh-indexer
sudo systemctl start wazuh-indexer
Step 1.3: Install Wazuh Dashboard
# Install Wazuh Dashboard
sudo apt install -y wazuh-dashboard

# Configure dashboard
sudo tee /etc/wazuh-dashboard/opensearch_dashboards.yml > /dev/null <<EOF
server.host: 0.0.0.0
server.port: 5601
opensearch.hosts: ["http://127.0.0.1:9200"]
opensearch.ssl.verificationMode: none
EOF

# Start Wazuh Dashboard
sudo systemctl enable wazuh-dashboard
sudo systemctl start wazuh-dashboard

# Access dashboard at http://YOUR_IP:5601
Step 1.4: Configure Local Wazuh Agent
# Install Wazuh Agent
sudo apt install -y wazuh-agent

# Configure agent to connect to local manager
sudo sed -i 's|<address>.*</address>|<address>127.0.0.1</address>|' /var/ossec/etc/ossec.conf

# Start agent
sudo systemctl enable wazuh-agent
sudo systemctl start wazuh-agent

# Verify agent connection
sudo /var/ossec/bin/agent_control -l
